<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray, Shokhin View Possibility of Positions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1901112094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1052 
GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1901112094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Aleksandrova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 19 Jan -- Sergey Shakhray, who is a member 
of the State Duma, told journalists during a break in today's 
session of the lower house that he will probably agree to head 
the Ministry of Nationality Affairs and Regional Policy. This 
is because he feels that 1994 will be quite a difficult year as 
far as interethnic relations are concerned. He voiced 
confidence that he would be able "to at least minimize" the 
consequences of interethnic conflicts and help resolve them. 
  Sergey Shakhray expressed the wish that, even if he does 
lose 
the post of deputy prime minister, he should at least be able to 
have direct access to the prime minister and deputy prime 
minister. 
  Asked by an ITAR-TASS correspondent about the prospects for 
his joining the new government, Deputy Aleksandr Shokhin said: 
"I cannot tell you anything new. I have not yet decided. The 
number of offers I am getting is increasing." 

</TEXT>

