<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Volskiy Continues To Refuse Offer To Join </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1901092394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0819 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1901092394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 19 TASS -- Arkadiy Volskiy, the 
president of the Russian Union of Industrialists and 
Entrepreneurs, turned down the offer to join the government 
which was, evidently, made to him by First Deputy Prime Minister 
Oleg Soskovets who attended the Tuesday meeting of Volskiy's 
union. 
  "I am repeating for the 37th time that I will not work in 
this government", Volskiy told TASS on Wednesday. He did not 
deny the fact that he had received the offer. 
  Volskiy's election bloc, the "Civic Union", lost the last 
parliamentary election completely which proved that directors of 
state enterprises which it united have no social support because 
of the failure to ensure the minimum subsistance level to their 
workers and to pay wages in time. 
  However, it is clear that Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin 
and his First Deputy Oleg Soskovets want to rely on heads of 
state run enterprises and farms in their future work. This 
explains the offer to Volsky and a resolute support to Deputy 
Prime Minister Aleksandr Zaveryukha who protects the interests 
of collective and state farms. 
  President Boris Yeltsin, who has accepted the resignation of 
Yegor Gaydar, the major reformer in the government, now insists 
on keeping another reformer, Finance Minister Boris Fedorov, in 
the government. This caused a major disagreement with the prime 
minister, as Fedorov insists that Zaveryukha be dismissed. 
  The decision on the final government composition is thus 
delayed. The presidential press service announced on Wednesday 
that consultations will continue today and in the coming days. 

</TEXT>

