<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shokhin Sees No Sharp Change in Government Line </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801202894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1845 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1801202894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Aleksandrova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 18 TASS -- Russian Vice Prime 
Minister Aleksandr Shokhin said on Tuesday it is unlikely that 
the government will sharply change its line, if its core remains 
intact. 
  At the same time, he admitted that it would be hard to 
resist 
the pressure from the industrial and regional lobby especially 
after the inflation spiral was wound tightly in the last four 
months. Now it is beginning to unwind, forcing the government 
to pay off the debts which were not paid in November-December, 
Shokhin said. 
  Even if former First Vice Prime Minister Yegor Gaydar 
decided 
to stay in the government, this process would continue anyway, 
he said. It is hard to imagine that under Gaydar inflation would 
be smaller in January-February than in December, Shokhin said. 

</TEXT>

