<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Party Leader: Chernomyrdin Wins Opposition Support </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801141094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1234 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1801141094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Yulia Kantor] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 18 TASS -- The resignation of First 
Deputy Premier Yegor Gaydar means that communists and other 
opposition blocs will now cooperate with the government of 
Viktor Chernomyrdin, according to Sergey Baburin, the leader of 
the hard-line "Russian Path" parliamentary group and a staunch 
opponent of President Boris Yeltsin. 
  "I believe the resignation of Yegor Gaydar signals the end 
of 
the transfer of the (pro-Yeltsin) Russia's Choice bloc into 
opposition", Baburin told TASS on Tuesday. 
  Now the communists and other opposition factions in 
parliament will "take under patronage Chernomyrdin and his 
government", he said. 

</TEXT>

