<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gorbachev: Gaydar's Resignation Changes Nothing </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1901133994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1221 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1901133994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Gaydar's resignation, and even a possible walk out 
of other "shock therapy symbols," will not change anything since 
the government does not have a clearly-defined line of 
development. That was declared in an interview with INTERFAX by 
Mikhail Gorbachev, the ex-Soviet president. 
  In his opinion, no one in the government is thinking about 
what should be done next to advance the country, and for this 
reason "we are doomed to political and economic drifting with 
all the ensuing consequences." 
  He warned that if the country's leaders "disregarded the 
popular mood, Russia would surely get into new serious political 
troubles with adverse social effects." 
  However, he spoke out against returning the country to the 
old system. In his words, the course towards a market economy 
should be continued but substantially corrected. 
  He suggested for one that market relations should be 
intensified at the small and medium business level and urged 
passing tough anti-monopoly legislation. 
  "But there is nothing more important than to teach people 
how 
to live under market conditions, otherwise transition to a 
market economy will be violent," Gorbachev stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

