<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Democratic Russia Movement To Oppose Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801133494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1305 
GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1801133494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Igor Belskiy] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 18 Jan (ITAR-TASS) -- The leaders of the 
Democratic Russia movement declared that they are moving across 
to the antigovernment camp. Following ultimatums on the 
membership of the government, the Coordinating Council of 
Democratic Russia announced today that it will act "as an 
opponent to the course of the government headed by Viktor 
Chernomyrdin." 
  The statement says that Russia is leaving the course of 
reform. The leaders of Democratic Russia believe that this is 
borne out by Yegor Gaydar's refusal to join the new government. 
"Gaydar's departure is in line with events and confirms the 
general tendency toward curtailing the course of reform in the 
country," the statement says. 
  The leaders of Democratic Russia are threatening to organize 
statements in the press, and also to hold mass acts of protest 
against the government's policies. The first meeting of 
Moscow's public has been set by the leaders of Democratic Russia 
for 22 January. 

</TEXT>

