<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dual Citizenship Seen as Security Threat </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1801162994 Tallinn ETA NEWS BULLETIN in English 0742 GMT 
18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS1801162994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn ETA NEWS BULLETIN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From 18 January RAHVA HAAL, p 1] </F>
  [Text] Tuesday, January 18 -- Estonian-Russian dual 
citizenship would present a major threat to Estonians national 
security, Minister for Ethnic Affairs Peeter Olesk warned. 
  "The introduction of the dual citizenship is an element of 
the Russian national policy that all the leading Russian 
ideologists have been calling for. It would enable a hidden 
restoration of the former Soviet Union," Olesk warned. 
  There are approximately 41,000 Russian citizens in Estonia, 
but it is difficult to establish, whether they have dual 
citizenship, since Russia is hiding the information, Olesk said. 
If the Estonian authorities do not know who the Russian 
citizens are, Russia can always consider any act directed 
against such persons as a provocation, the minister warned. 
These persons will be used as tools in case Russia needs to 
prove violations of human rights in Estonia, Olesk predicted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

