<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Briefing Held on Russian-U.S. Missile Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801142794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1417 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1801142794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS analyst Vladimir Gondusov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 18 TASS -- The pledge made by the 
Russian and American presidents at their Moscow summit to target 
Russian and American missiles away from the major cities of the 
two countries before May 30, 1994 was largely political and 
diplomatic in nature, intended to demonstrate a warmer 
relationship between Moscow and Washington, a briefing in the 
Russian Defence Ministry was told today. 
  As concerns the military aspect of the relevant clause in 
the 
Moscow declaration, which Yeltsin and Clinton signed last week, 
the change of targets reduces the first-strike threat, the risk 
of an unsanctioned launch, and thereby the danger of nuclear war 
in general, according to Major-General Anatoliy Svetikov, who 
represented the Russian strategic missile forces at the briefing. 
  The presidents promised to re-target their missiles not 
later 
than May 30, 1994. But in actual fact, target coordinates can 
be changed within 15 to 20 minutes, the general said. 
  According to specialists, the procedure is not very 
complicated -- the target coordinates which can guide a missile 
to the United States or Russia will be replaced in the missile 
computer memory with the coordinates of one or another deserted 
areas in the world ocean. 
  According to American sources, about twenty such areas have 
been identified to become the main targets in the missile 
computer memories. Reserve coordinates will be saved in the 
memory as well. If all coordinates are deleted from memory, the 
missile can hit land in the same area from which it was launched. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-56772 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov012_a_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-012 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 January 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian, U.S. Envoys to UN Comment on Moscow Summit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1901102694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0808 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1901102694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Sitnikov] </F>
  [Text] United Nations January 19 TASS -- Russian Permanent 
Delegate at the United Nations Yuliy Vorontsov and U.S. 
Permanent Delegate at the United Nations Madeleine Albright made 
a joint statement to journalists accredited at the U.N. 
headquarters on Tuesday concerning the results of the Moscow 
summit meeting. 
  The Russian and American representatives drew the attention 
of world public opinion to an important item of the Moscow 
declaration, signed by the Presidents of Russia and the United 
States, in which they have reaffirmed their support to the 
United Nations Organisation and called for joint efforts to 
strengthen the U.N. peacekeeping role. Vorontsov and Albright 
stated in part: 
  "Both presidents have stressed the need to strengthen the 
U.N. ability to keep the peace and prevent conflicts. They made 
it incumbent on our two governments to work jointly in order to 
improve the mechanism in this sphere. We express mutual 
satisfaction, and this is particularly important, that our two 
presidents have called for a Security Council meeting at summit 
level to mark the 50th anniversary of the United Nations. 
  "It is clear that by making this statement, both Russia and 
the United States thereby recognise and prize the central role 
played by the United Nations, particularly, the U.N. 
peacekeeping operations and efforts to safeguard international 
peace and security in this increasingly chaotic and unstable 
world." 
  The Russian and American representatives also stated that 
they would cooperate closely in the effort to ensure the success 
of the U.N. Security Council meeting at summit level, proposed 
by the Presidents of Russia and the United States. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

