<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Council Discusses Hardware Development </TI></H3>
<H4>   Agenda for Meeting Previewed </H4>
<F P=102> LD1801162194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1454 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1801162194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] INTERFAX has learned that a session of the RF 
[Russian Federation] Security Council to be chaired by Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin is to be held on Wednesday, January 19. 
Well-informed sources assert that the agenda will include 
several issues related to the development of Russia's military 
doctrine confirmed by the Security Council last November. In 
particular, it is to consider several military-technical aspects 
of the doctrine. 
  This document contains a model of the defensive-industrial 
complex activity under the system of market relations. 
Competitive development of arms proclaimed by the doctrine must 
rule out harmful parallelism in creation and development of 
various kinds of armaments and to provide for rational spending 
of allocated funds. 
  High quality of the Russian army's military equipment should 
enjoy priority. The document stresses that military equipment 
of the Russian army should obligatorily correspond to world 
standards. 
  The session to be held behind closed doors is to consider 
several issues regarding recent reshuffles in the supreme 
echelons of power. 

</TEXT>

