<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gamsakhurdia's Family Agrees to Post Mortem </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1201164594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1433 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1201164594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The family of Zviad Gamsakhurdia has agreed to a 
post mortem examination of the body of the Georgian 
ex-president, who committed suicide on the night from December 
31 to January 1 in Western Georgia. The examination must be 
held with international observers, Interfax learnt from sources 
in the Georgian Prosecutor General's Office. 
  A Georgian Security Ministry spokesman has told Interfax 
that 
the arrival in the republic of international experts and members 
of the Gamsakhurdia family is possible shortly. 
  Zviadists who control the village of Djikhashkari in western 
Georgia where Gamsakhurdia is presumably buried are not so far 
allowing representatives of the present authorities or 
journalists to the village. 
  The village is guarded, Interfax was told, by a large group 
of Zviadists who are armed with tanks, artillery pieces and 
rocket launchers. 
  As it has become known to Interfax from unofficial sources, 
representatives of the Georgian authorities are negotiating the 
issue with Zviadists. The talks have provided no results yet 
because the authorities demand the extradition of Gamsakhurdia's 
body and Zviadists' disarmament. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

