<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Adopts Decree on Electric Power </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1301105294 Tbilisi First Program Television Network in 
Georgian 1700 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1301105294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi First Program Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Georgian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Republic of Georgia Cabinet of Ministers has 
adopted a decree on the supply of fuel and electric power to 
economic complexes and the population during the first three 
months of 1994. According to this decree, a reduction in the 
supply of thermal power and the economical use of existing fuel 
and power resources are viewed as a task of particular 
importance. The appropriate institutions and departments are 
entrusted with reducing street lighting and all kinds of neon 
advertising by 50 percent and regulating independent sources of 
electric power. 
  According to the decree, schedules for the supply, 
production, use, and allocation of gas and electric power have 
to be established. The 5,000 tonnes of (?kerosene) that has 
arrived in the form of humanitarian aid from Japan is to be 
taken into consideration. 
  It is stated in the decree that, in addition to local 
administrative bodies, the Republic of Georgia Ministry of 
Internal Affairs and the Ministry of Defense should ensure the 
protection of electric power installations in Georgia. 

</TEXT>

