<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Compensation for Uranium Viewed at Briefing </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1801171494 Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network in 
Ukrainian 1500 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS1801171494 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Comments on the tripartite negotiations by the 
Ukrainian, American, and Russian presidents that took place on 
18 January in Moscow were presented at a briefing held at the 
Ukrainian Foreign Ministry. In particular, it was noted that 
the tripartite declaration adopted at the negotiations is a 
document containing political obligations regarding moving 
toward nuclear disarmament. It is of crucial importance for 
Ukraine because since the entire rocket-launching infrastructure 
is stationed outside of Ukraine, nuclear weapons are not a 
deterring factor for our state, as well as because the rockets, 
whose storage expiration terms are already ending, pose a 
serious environmental threat to Ukraine itself. So the juggling 
of some Ukrainian political forces with people's patriotic 
feelings inflicts only damages. Responding to a question about 
compensating Ukraine for the value of the enriched uranium 
contained in warheads that are located on its territory, the 
briefing organizers said that it will be provided in the form of 
heat-emitting elements for (?Alpha). At the negotiations, Bill 
Clinton reiterated the U.S. pledge to allocate about $800 
million for Russia, Ukraine, Kazakhstan, and Belarus to heighten 
safety [words indistinct] nuclear forces and storage of 
decomposable materials. At the initial stage, Ukraine will 
receive $175 million. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-56789 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov014_e_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-014 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

