<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kiev `Not Obliged' To Inform Moscow of Nuclear Accidents </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2001203394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1715 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2001203394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Chairman of Ukrainian Gosatomnadzor (state committee 
for supervising safety requirements at nuclear power stations) 
Nikolay Steinberg believes that Kiev is "not obliged to inform 
Moscow of all accidents at Ukrainian nuclear power stations 
since we have not signed any bilateral agreements on exchange of 
nuclear information." 
  In an interview with INTERFAX-Ukraine, Steinberg pointed out 
that "there exists a coherent international system for the 
notification of the nuclear situation in the world, under which 
all members of the European Nuclear Society inform the 
headquarters of this organization based in Switzerland of 
accidents at their nuclear power stations, which distributes the 
information among the other member-states." 
  Meanwhile, the head of the press service of the Russian 
Gosatomnadzor, Yuriy Rogozhin, told INTERFAX yesterday that 
failures to inform the Russian Gosatomnadzor by former Soviet 
republics violate the official agreement between the nuclear 
supervising organizations reached shortly after the break-up of 
the Soviet Union. 

</TEXT>

