<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ukraine, PRC Envoys Discuss Nuclear Disarmament </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801214794 Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service in Ukrainian 
2000 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1801214794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On 18 January Anatoliy Plyushko, Ukrainian 
ambassador to the People's Republic of China, had a meeting with 
(Dai Bingo), PRC assistant foreign affairs minister. The 
ambassador gave a detailed account of the results of the meeting 
between the Ukrainian, U.S., and Russian presidents in Moscow 
and the contents of the declaration they signed. It was 
emphasized that the accords, reached as the result of the 
meeting, on providing Ukraine with security guarantees, as well 
as financial and technological assistance for eliminating 
nuclear weapons and compensation for uranium contained in 
nuclear warheads were creating the necessary conditions for 
gradual elimination of the nuclear weapons deployed on Ukrainian 
soil and for Ukraine to attain nonnuclear status. It said that 
the accords, to a considerable degree, were resolving the 
problems that caused the Ukrainian Supreme Council to have 
reservations about ratifying the START I treaty and the Lisbon 
protocol. 
  The hope was expressed that, as a nuclear power and 
permanent 
member of the UN Security Council, China would play an active 
part in settling the issue of nuclear disarmament in Ukraine 
and, in particular, of providing Ukraine with security 
guarantees and financial assistance in order to eliminate the 
nuclear weapons deployed on its territory. 

</TEXT>

