<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tours Aircraft Center With Kravchuk </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2001194394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1710 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2001194394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By UKRINFORM correspondents Viktor Demidenko and Alexey </F>
Petrunya] 
  [Text] Kiev January 20 TASS -- The Antonov scientific and 
technical aircraft centre has designed a new air liner, AN-70 
transport aircraft, which is to be produced by three former 
Soviet republics -- Ukraine, Russia and Kazakhstan. 
  The rollout ceremony was attended by Presidents Leonid 
Kravchuk of Ukraine and Nursultan Nazarbayev of Kazakhstan, who 
is currently on an official visit to Ukraine. 
  According to chief designer Pyotr Balabuyev, the new plane 
is 
intended for carrying cargoes and equipment by civil aviation 
and the air force. The aircraft can carry up to 30-35 tons of 
cargoes for a distance up to 4,000-5,000 km at a speed of 
750-800 km/h. The first air liners are expected to be put into 
service already in 1996. 
  Experts believe that the new aircraft can replace the 
U.S.-made C-130 Hercules and the European-made C-160 Transol 
presently used in West European countries. 

</TEXT>

