<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze Seeks Forensic Test on Gamsakhurdia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1901215794 Tbilisi First Program Television Network in 
Georgian 2055 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1901215794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi First Program Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Georgian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] International experts have been in Tbilisi for 
several days now. At the invitation of the Georgian Health 
Ministry, they are to take part in a forensic examination of 
Zviad Gamsakhurdia's body. 
  According to messages published in the press, members of the 
ex-president's family categorically rule out the possibility of 
carrying out a forensic examination, and set other categorical 
conditions. 
  A SAKINFORM correspondent asked Head of State Eduard 
Shevardnadze to assess the current situation. He said: The 
will of God is involved in the birth of every person. 
Therefore, anybody's departure from this world is a regrettable 
event. This also applies to ex-Georgian president Gamsakhurdia. 
One should not talk now about who is to blame for the disasters 
that have befallen the country. As for the decision on the 
place of burial, this is an exclusive privilege of the family. 
The burial can take place in Groznyy, as demanded by the 
family. The Georgian authorities regard the request to carry 
out an international forensic examination as completely lawful, 
despite the fact that the ex-president's family opposes this. 
Of course, this can only happen after the place where the 
deceased was buried is revealed. 
  I think that any sensible person would agree, Eduard 
Shevardnadze pointed out, if I say that the cause of Zviad 
Gamsakhurdia's death should not be wrapped in mystery and people 
should know the truth. This is why it is necessary to carry out 
an examination. 
  A group is working at the Georgian Cabinet of Ministers 
which 
is entrusted with reaching agreement on these issues with Zviad 
Gamsakhurdia's wife. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

