<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Explanation of Russia's Foreign Policy Sought </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2001210294 Tallinn ETA NEWS RELEASE in English 1855 GMT 20 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS2001210294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn ETA NEWS RELEASE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, January 20 -- Despite the correction, on 
Wednesday [19 January], by the Russian officials, of Russian 
Minister of Foreign Affairs Kozyrev's some statements, 
concerning the Baltic states and the CIS member states, Russia 
has not dismissed its general viewpoint on the matter, presented 
by Kozyrev, which should be a cause of anxiety to the 
international community, Raul Malk, acting head of office of the 
Estonian Ministry of Foreign Affairs told ETA, on Thursday. 
  "Russia's view that it had `strategic interests' in relation 
to its `near abroad' and it would not give up what has been 
fought for for so much, is different from the contents of the 
declaration signed at the summit of Russia and the USA," Malk 
said, adding that this should still be a cause of anxiety for 
other countries. 
  "The world expects Russia to present an explanation as to 
its 
attitude towards other states," he stressed. At the summit of 
the USA and Russia both sides talked about the fact that no 
divisional lines should be drawn in Europe, Malk said, stressing 
that calling some states "near abroad" means in itself drawing 
divisional lines. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

