<H3> <TI>   Reinart Appointed Leader of Delegation to Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1901154794 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 19 Jan 94 
First Edition p 6 </F>

<F P=103> PM1901154794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [INTERFAX report: "New Leader Appointed"] </F>
  [Text] The Estonian Government has appointed Vaino 
Reinart, leader of the Estonian Ministry of Foreign Affairs 
First Bureau, as leader of the Estonian delegation to the 
Estonian-Russian interstate negotiations, INTERFAX reports. 
  As Estonian Prime Minister Mart Laar reported at a press 
conference in Tallinn Tuesday [18 January], several days ago 
President Lennart Meri conferred on V. Reinart the diplomatic 
rank of special envoy, "the same as Russian delegation head 
Vasiliy Svirin." The premier noted that V. Reinart had 
previously been a member of the Estonian delegation and knows 
well the specific nature of the negotiations. 
  In conversation with an INTERFAX correspondent, M. Laar 
refuted the accusations made in Moscow by Sergey Stepashin, 
first deputy director of the Russian Federal Counterintelligence 
Service, that the Estonian secret services were engaged in 
intelligence work against Russia. "Estonia does not engage in 
intelligence work against Russia," the prime minister emphasized. 

</TEXT>

