<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Will Not Alter Stance on Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2001200494 Tallinn BNS in English 1619 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2001200494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Jan 20, BNS -- Latvia received the full text 
of Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev's comments but they 
did not prompt the Foreign Ministry to alter its previous 
negative stance on the statements, Minister Georgs Andrejevs 
told BNS. 
  Latvia's response to Kozyrev's statements was not reckless 
because the full text of his speech contains the same ideas of 
continued military presence in the Baltic region as the 
ITAR-TASS news agency reported earlier. 
  The Jan. 19 statement by Baltic prime ministers also does 
not 
misconstrue Kozyrev's words in the conference of Russian 
diplomatic corps representatives. 
  Andrejevs described Kozyrev's comments as ambigous. They 
allow for various interpretations, the minister noted. 
  The Latvian Government was also troubled because the 
statement followed President Bill Clinton's visit to Moscow, 
Andrejevs said. 
  The U.S. State Department, however, demanded Russian 
clarifications on the statement "if the news accounts on 
Kozyrev's comments are accurate." 
  This leads to believe that Russia did not coordinate its 
political course with the U.S. Government, Andrejevs said. 
  State Department spokesman Michael McCurry said Jan. 19 that 
Kozyrev's comments are "certainly at odds with statements by 
President Yeltsin in Moscow and certainly (are) at odds with 
things that we've been told by high officials of the Russian 
Government in our meetings in Moscow and prior to Moscow." 
  As reported, Kozyrev spoke out against a complete withdrawal 
of Russian troops from the Baltics and other former states of 
the Soviet Union because of Russia's vital interests. 

</TEXT>

