<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S., Russia Said To Agree on Russian Presence </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1901165894 Riga Radio Riga Network in Latvian 1401 GMT 19 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1901165894 </F>
<F P=104>  Riga Radio Riga Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Latvian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Aleksandrs Kirsteins, chairman of the Foreign 
Affairs Commission of the Saeima, does not consider as a change 
in Russian foreign policy toward the Baltic states the views 
expressed by the Russian foreign minister on Tuesday regarding a 
need for Russian military presence in the republics of the 
former Soviet Union. According to Kirsteins, Kozyrev's remarks 
are only partly related to the recent visit by U.S. President 
Clinton to Moscow, because statements made by U.S. Secretary of 
State Warren Christopher during his recent visit to Latvia are 
already evidence of the existence of an agreement between the 
United States and Russia that Russia should maintain a military 
presence in Latvia. 
  It has been clear for a long time that Russia will not leave 
Latvia of its own accord and that it does not wish to withdraw 
its troops from the Baltics, Kirsteins explained. He noted that 
Russia always interprets differently remarks made by its 
officials, and it is therefore necessary to receive from the 
Russian Government a more detailed explanation of Kozyrev's 
statement in the near future. 

</TEXT>

