<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official on Appointment of Deputy Premiers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1901202994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1939 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1901202994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A plenipotentiary representative of the chairman of 
the government of the Russian Federation, head of the press 
service of the government Valentin Sergeyev said that the widely 
used formula "governmental crisis" is far-fetched in the view of 
Victor Chernomyrdin. Ministries and departments which were not 
subject to reorganization under a recent Presidential decree 
function normally. The composition of the heads of these 
ministries was not reviewed. 
  As for the new appointments, first of all in the upper 
echelons of executive power, all the candidates have been agreed 
upon between Victor Chernomyrdin and Boris Yeltsin and the 
decree on their appointments was signed on January 18, V. 
Sergeyev noted. 
  He also reported that Victor Chernomyrdin "was very 
skeptical 
about the enthusiasm of volunteers who suggested to form a new 
government or who stand up for the resignation of the present 
cabinet. There is no need to do it," V. Sergeyev quoted the 
prime minister as saying, "the government exists, it works and 
continues the course of reforms." 
  When asked about who was appointed the vice premier V. 
Sergeyev named the First Vice Premier Oleg Soskovets. Aleksandr 
Zaveryukha, Anatoliy Chubays and Yuriy Yarov were appointed vice 
premiers. 
  The decree of the President of the Russian Federation B. 
Yeltsin on the main appointments will be published on January 
20, said V. Sergeyev. 
  Meanwhile Interfax has learned that the decree on the 
government has not yet reached the presidential office. 
  According to some unofficial reports Boris Fedorov may 
remain 
in the position of the finance minister, while Aleksandr Shokhin 
was appointed the economics minister. 
  Other sources from the entourage of the prime minister V. 
Chernomyrdin noted in their turn that the issue of B. Fedorov's 
presence in the reorganized government had not been settled so 
far. 

</TEXT>

