<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Resignation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2001220394 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
2020 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2001220394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Finance Minister Boris Fedorov announced his 
resignation at a news conference today. The decision had been 
made as far back as 18 January. 
  Fedorov's disagreement in principle with the new economic 
policy of the government which is being formed at present was 
the reason for his resignation. Fedorov also finds it is 
impossible for him to stay at his post together with chairman of 
the Central Bank Viktor Gerashchenko. Since the president has 
kept Gerashchenko, Fedorov has chosen to resign. 
  The ex-minister said there would be no headlong drop in the 
ruble exchange rate in the immediate future since the foundation 
of the financial policy had been laid for three months in 
advance. He predicted a worsening of the financial situation in 
April. 
  Fedorov said he did not know of any other policy in the 
conditions of market economy except monetarist, and any attempts 
to improve the industry by issuing money will only lead to 
higher inflation. 
  He sharply criticized the agreement between the Russian 
Central Bank and Belarus on the single monetary zone. He 
expressed the opinion that Russia would bear the burden of the 
decision. 
  Among his merits, Fedorov mentioned the ruble's relatively 
stable rate and an increase in the real income of the population 
by 10 percent in 1993. 
  [Begin Fedorov recording] A populist policy which, I think, 
will be chosen, threatens with the ruble rate reaching 12,000 by 
the end of the year, average inflation rates -- approximately 30 
percent and falling real living standards. At the same time 
production will still fall by about five per cent. So none of 
the indices will improve. But, as I already said in my New Year 
forecast, it is possible that the production of tanks might 
increase. [end recording] 
  Fedorov refused to name his candidate for the post of 
finance 
minister fearing that, if he named him, the latter would have 
not been appointed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

