<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Cites Fedorov on Resignation Decision </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2101101794 Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI in Russian 21 Jan 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> PM2101101794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Igor Petrov report: "Boris Fedorov: I Have No Reason To </F>
Resign As Yet"] 
  [Text] "I do not believe that the decision to build a 
parliamentary center or even the agreement on monetary union 
with Belarus can be sufficient grounds for my resignation," 
Boris Fedorov, vice premier and minister of finance, told your 
ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI correspondent. "I will not take this step 
until I judge government policy in the credit and monetary 
sphere to have changed so much as to constitute the end of 
reforms." 
  According to Boris Fedorov, one such indicator for him might 
be a considerable increase in the ceiling on the issue of credit 
in the first quarter of 1994. "If under pressure from all 
manner of lobbies the government issues over 10 trillion rubles 
in Central Bank credit, there can be no question of any 
financial stabilization," the minister believes. 
  In Fedorov's opinion, what is now being observed on the 
money 
market is quite natural. "We are on the verge of a change of 
economic policy and the money market is responding appropriately 
to this." 
  Boris Fedorov does not believe that he set the prime 
minister 
"deliberately unacceptable terms" in demanding that Aleksandr 
Zaveryukha and Viktor Gerashchenko be removed from government. 
"We are talking about the country's future, about what the 
government's strategic course will be, and how it will affect 
millions of Russian citizens. I can only be accountable for 
that which has been entrusted to me if I have a chance of 
influencing it." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

