<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-014 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Filippov Says Yeltsin Formed `Compromise' Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101111794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1106 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2101111794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Amara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 21 TASS -- Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin could not form a government at his own will, according 
to Petr Filippov, the head of the analytical centre of the 
presidential administration. 
  "Boris Yeltsin has to keep balance between various forces", 
he told TASS on Friday evidently meaning that the current 
government composition was a compromise of the president. 
  An adequate substitution for Boris Fedorov, who had resigned 
as the finance minister, may be his first deputy Sergey Dubinin, 
Filippov said. 
  Noted economist Grigoriy Yavlinskiy would hardly be invited 
to fill in the remaining vacant post of the first deputy prime 
minister, he added. 
  "I think that Viktor Chernomyrdin will try to keep Oleg 
Soskovets as his only first deputy", Filippov said and added 
that he personally does not believe in Yavlinskiy's ability to 
reform the economy. 
  "I do not believe in the possibility of reforming economy on 
the basis of speculative schemes like the '500 days' programme", 
he explained referring to the programme which Yavlinskiy had 
offered yet to former Soviet president Mikhail Gorbachev, but 
which was turned down. 

</TEXT>

