<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin Denies `Crisis' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2001145794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1416 
GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2001145794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Gennadiy Talalayev] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 20 Jan--There is no crisis in the 
government, it is continuing its work, and rumors of a crisis 
are far-fetched, Viktor Chernomyrdin, head of the Council of 
Ministers, said today. 
  Speaking at a news conference for Russian and foreign 
journalists, Chernomyrdin stressed that "the course of 
continuing and deepening reforms that was adopted in 1993 
remains unchanged, and the government will not retreat from it". 
  The head of the government said: "Crisis phenomena are 
subsiding much more slowly than was expected. January of this 
year is being marked by an exacerbation of financial problems 
and a serious acceleration of inflation". At present, the 
average weekly increase in prices is over 4 percent, and the 
volume of output is only 85 percent of the December level. 
  The prime minister said that there would be an enlarged 
session of the government sometime during the first 10 days of 
February, at which there would be detailed discussion of "what 
has been successful, what has been unsuccessful, and why and 
what needs to be done as a priority task in 1994". 

</TEXT>

