<H3> <TI>   Accepts Post </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2001091194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0857 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2001091194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Ivan Novikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 20 TASS -- Sergey Shakray said on 
Thursday that he had accepted the proposal to become the 
minister for national and regional affairs in the new 
government, the position he had actually held before December 12 
elections. 
  Shakhray, the leader of the Party of Russian Unity and 
Accord 
parliamentary faction, also hinted at a press conference that 
Aleksandr Shokhin, a member of his party, was appointed 
economics minister to replace Yegor Gaydar who had resigned. 
  "As far as I know the decree about this has not been signed 
yet, but this will, evidently, take place today", he said. 
  Shakhray and Shokhin were both deputy premiers, but most 
evidently will lose the status in the new composition of the 
government. 
  On Wednesday a government spokesman said that Oleg Soskovets 
will be the first deputy prime minister, while Aleksandr 
Zaveryukha, Yuriy Yarov and Anatoliy Chubais will be deputy 
premiers. 
  There are to be two first deputy premiers and three deputy 
premiers in the new government, according to a presidential 
decision. 

</TEXT>

