<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Shakhray Press Conference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2101103394 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 21 Jan 94 First 
Edition p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM2101103394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed untitled report] </F>
  [Text] Despite the fact that the president's edict on the 
composition of the government has not yet been signed, S. 
Shakhray has already announced that he has accepted an offer to 
fill the post of minister for nationalities and regional policy 
in the new cabinet. 
  He made this statement at a press conference held on the 
morning of 20 January in the State Duma building. According to 
S. Shakhray, he is totally unperturbed at the reduction in his 
status from vice premier to "mere" minister. He sees his main 
task as being to ensure that the ministry he has been instructed 
to head works effectively. He also hinted at the possibility 
that the ministry will be directly subordinate to Chernomyrdin. 
  S. Shakhray also disclosed that, together with his party and 
Duma faction colleague A. Shokhin, he has been subjected to 
strong pressure from the PRUA [Party of Russian Unity and 
Accord]. The party demanded that they remain in the government. 
If only as ministers. The PRUA leader confirmed that A. 
Shokhin has agreed to become economics minister. 
  In this connection S. Shakhray unexpectedly sharply 
criticized Ye. Gaydar's departure from the government and the 
possible departure of B. Fedorov. In particular, he stated that 
the present complex situation in Russia "is in many respects 
their handiwork." In his opinion, difficulties within the 
government, which Ye. Gaydar cited as the explanation of his 
decision to go, are objectively inevitable and it is dishonest 
to quit because of them. 
  In answering numerous questions about the consequences of 
the 
government reshuffle, S. Shakhray expressed confidence that no 
political force today will now be able to abandon reforms. 

</TEXT>

