<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shokhin Accepts Post as Economics Minister </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2001174494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1447 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2001174494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Deputy Prime Minister Aleksandr Shokhin told 
journalists that he had met with President Boris Yeltsin 
Thursday and accepted the president's official offer of the 
position of economics minister in the new government. 
  Shokhin had been assured direct access to the prime 
minister. 
He will not have to report to deputy prime ministers. 
  Shokhin also said that Finance Minister Boris Fedorov was 
awaiting a reply to his conditions for staying in the government. 
  Shokhin, who had spoken with him on the telephone Thursday 
morning, believed that Fedorov could join the government if just 
one of his conditions, dismissal of Viktor Gerashchenko from 
governorship of the Central Bank, was met. Fedorov had earlier 
said that he would not stay in the government if Aleksandr 
Zaveryukha remained a deputy prime minister. 
  Shokhin thought that if Fedorov left the government, his 
duties would be taken over by one of his deputies, for example 
Sergey Dubinin, or former finance minister Vasiliy Barchuk. 
  Shokhin said that the protracted formation of a new cabinet 
was tantamount to a governmental crisis. 

</TEXT>

