<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   States Government Not Fully Reorganized </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2001174394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1628 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2001174394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] "Russia's government has not been finally 
reorganized yet," Deputy Premier and a leading member of the 
Party of Russian Unity and Accord, Alekander Shokhin, told 
journalists on Thursday. A decision concerning Boris Fedorov's 
remaining in the government has not been taken yet. 
  Fedorov advanced a number of conditions, largely concerning 
individual officials, for his joining the reorganized Cabinet, 
Shokhin noted. 
  "I know that the prime minister and the president have 
different views as to the possibility of meeting Fedorov's 
conditions," Shokhin said. 
  Fedorov had said he would join the government if Deputy 
Premier Aleksander Zaveryukha, responsible for agriculture, and 
the Central Bank Governor Victor Gerashchenko leave the Cabinet. 
  According to Shokhin, the candidacy of another first deputy 
premier (one of these posts has already been reserved for Oleg 
Soskovets) is under consideration now. "This job will obviously 
not remain unfilled," Shokhin said. 
  When asked whether Fedorov is likely to become the other 
first deputy premier, Shokhin said, "I don't know." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

