<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   TV Satellite Onboard Proton Launch </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2001125394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1239 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2001125394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Semen Ivanov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 20 TASS -- The Russian space military 
forces launched the first TV satellite called "Gals" with a 
"Proton" three-stage booster-rocket from the Baykonur 
Cosmodrome on Thursday at 12:49, Moscow time. ITAR-TASS learnt 
at the press centre of the space military forces that the 
launching was successful. 
  The satellite was developed by the applied mechanics 
scientific and production amalgamation (Krasnoyarsk-26) under 
the guidance of chief designer and general manager Mikhail 
Reshetnev. 
  The launching pioneers a system of direct space TV 
broadcasting, which will consist of five "Gals" satellites, for 
all information space of the Commonwealth of Independent States. 
  The satellite is equipped with a three-segment onboard relay 
which will ensure for the first time the reception of regional 
TV broadcasting with small-size individual antennae with a 
diameter 0.6-0.9 meters over individual Russian regions. The 
satellite weighs 2.5 tonnes and will operate for five or seven 
years in orbit. 
  The satellite will be put into orbit close to geostationary 
at a point 90 degrees of eastern longitude some seven hours 
after the launching. Following this, it will be brought to the 
point of "stationing" 44 degrees eastern longitude where it will 
be used for the assigned mission. 
  The "Gals" satellite is the first unmanned spacecraft 
blasted 
off by Russia this year. 

</TEXT>

