<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Removes Crimean Envoy From Duties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2001092694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0855 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2001092694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Roman Zadunaiskiy] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 20 TASS -- Ukrainian President Leonid 
Kravchuk signed a decree on Wednesday, removing Ivan Yermakov 
from the post of presidential representative in Sevastopol, 
sources close to the presidential office reported on Thursday. 
  Kravchuk temporarily transferred the duties of his 
representative in Sevastopol to Nikolay Glushko, first deputy 
head of the city administration. 
  ITAR-TASS learnt at the press centre of the Black Sea Fleet 
later in the day that the Union of Afghan Veterans, the 
Sevastopol Russian community, the Crimean Movement of Voters, 
the union in support of the Crimean Republic and the leadership 
of city social services voiced support for Yermakov. 
  It is expected that the Sevastopol city council will call a 
special session in the near future to discuss Yermakov's 
resignation. 
  Local analysts believe that the resignation of the 
presidential representative in Sevastopol was caused by his 
participation in the election campaign as a candidate for the 
post of Crimean president. 
  Yermakov made repeated statements during the campaign that 
the problem of the Black Sea Fleet should be resolved in favour 
of Russia. 
  According to analysts, Kiev was also evidently riled by the 
fact that Yermakov did not support the candidacy of Crimean 
Parliament Speaker Nikolay Bahrov during the election campaign. 

</TEXT>

