<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Attack on Rukh Offices, Missing Official Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2001114294 Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY in Ukrainian 19 Jan 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> AU2001114294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "An Armed Attack on the Rukh </F>
Secretariat. Mysterious Disappearance of Its Chairman"] 
  [Text] Overnight between 15 and 16 January, an armed attack 
was made on the Rukh [Ukraine People's Movement for Perestroyka] 
Secretariat in Kiev. As reported by RUKH-PRESS, two unknown 
persons, claiming that they had to hand a package of documents 
from Lvov to chairman of the Secretariat Mykhaylo Boychyshyn, 
entered the reception room together with a watchman. As 
Mykhaylo Boychyshyn was not there, the visitors started 
telephoning him at home. After the call, which seems to have 
remained unanswered, one of the attackers pulled out a pistol. 
Hitting the guard on the head twice, he ordered that the 
chairman of the Secretariat be found immediately. After the 
watchman's refusal to fulfill the order, the attackers demanded 
that another guard they had noticed before, be summoned. The 
latter offered resistance and locked himself up in a room. The 
RUKH-PRESS head, who was at work at the time, immediately called 
the militia. Before the militiamen appeared, the armed "guests" 
managed to escape. On the same day, chairman of the Secretariat 
Mykhaylo Boychyshyn, who had left the office about three hours 
prior to the attack, disappeared. His whereabouts are still not 
known. The day before, the premises of the Ternopil regional 
organization of Rukh were also subject to an armed attack. At 
night, unknown persons got into the building through the second 
floor window, broke the doors of the Information Center and of 
other offices, and carried out a pogrom there. Having made 
their way to the roof of the building, the offenders dismantled 
and stole the installation for satellite antenna reception. 
Law-enforcement organs have started an investigation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

