<H3> <TI>   Rukh Protests `Terrorist Acts' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2001193694 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 1406 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2001193694 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kiev -- A session of the central leadership of the 
People's Movement of Ukraine [Rukh] took place on 19 January. 
Three statements were adopted at the session. The statement 
regarding terrorist acts against People's Movement of Ukraine 
activists names numerous events, which have occurred in many 
oblasts of Ukraine, in particular the disappearance of Mykhaylo 
Boychyshyn, head of the Rukh secretariat, without a trace on the 
night of 15 January, and the reflection is expressed that 
"certain circles in the state are endeavoring to demoralize the 
democratic forces on the eve of elections and frighten their 
adherents by means of terror." 
  The central leadership of Rukh evaluates the tripartite 
statement on eliminating nuclear weapons in Ukraine as 
"capitulation by Ukrainian state officials to gross external 
pressure," which became possible as a result of the lack of a 
clear and consistent foreign policy by the government. The 
leadership of Rukh believes that Leonid Kravchuk, president of 
Ukraine, took a capitulatory step. 
  Evaluating the results of the presidential elections in the 
Crimea, the central leadership of Rukh stated that the 
president's policy, aimed at pacifying the separatist forces, 
failed totally. The leadership of Rukh believes that a further 
delay of resolute actions by the president and Supreme Council 
of Ukraine regarding the stirring up of separatism in the Crimea 
could lead to armed conflict and irremediable consequences for 
the citizens of Ukraine and peace in Europe. 

</TEXT>

