<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Favors Balanced Division of Powers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801211994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1924 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1801211994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At a Tuesday conference of representatives of 
government bodies of all levels in Kiev, Ukrainian President 
Leonid Kravchuk supported the proposal on the removal of the 
president from the system of executive power. "The president 
should not be placed above everyone, just beyond the executive 
branch of power. He should control, but not interfere," 
Kravchuk said. 
  He described as the chief stabilizing factor "a balance of 
the powers between branches of government and their democratic 
transformation." Kravchuk promised that presidential structures 
would do their utmost to hold parliamentary elections in Ukraine 
and bring "qualified and loyal deputies" to the new parliament. 
However, in his opinion the elections are not the last step in 
reforming the system of government. Ukraine needs an integral 
system with a clear separation of powers. 
  The president also spoke for holding a referendum on key 
provisions of the constitution simultaneously with the 
parliamentary elections on March 27. He confirmed his proposal 
to drop from the fundamental law provisions concerning the 
official language, state symbol, and flag, the state order and 
other matters that might cause political confrontation. 
  On the latest developments in Crimea, Kravchuk said he 
believes the new constitution should declare that the executive 
branch of power in the autonomous republic be formed and act on 
the basis of the constitution and legislation of Ukraine as well 
as the Crimean constitution that should conform with the 
Ukrainian fundamental law. 
  Kravchuk suggested amending the constitution offering 
president powers to cancel the decisions of the Crimean 
parliament, if they contradict acting Ukrainian legislation. 
  The speaker of parliament Ivan Plyushch promised that such 
an 
amendment would be made and the conference voted for including 
the matter in the final document. 
  The president agreed with the proposals of participants to 
cut down the staffs of executive bodies of all levels by 
25%. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-56907 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov014_f_94011" </HT>


