<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   No `Major Disputes' in Border Talks With Poland </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2001202694 Tallinn BNS in English 1619 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2001202694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jan 20, BNS -- Lithuanian and Polish 
Government delegations signed on Thursday [20 January] a 
protocol of the first round of talks on state border 
delimitation and revision. Lithuania and Poland both recognize 
the inviolability of the present border. 
  The delegations, led by Vladislovas Domarkas, Lithuanian 
deputy minister of foreign affairs, and Eugeniusz Zuziak, 
representative of the Polish border guard chief commandant's 
headquarters, meet in Vilnius Jan. 17-21. 
  The Eastern Europe Division of the Lithuanian Foreign 
Ministry said the first round goes smoothly and without any 
major disputes. 
  Reportedly, an agreement on state border and legal relations 
in the border zone will be completed during the second round of 
talks. The delegations are scheduled to meet again in Warsaw in 
March or April. 

</TEXT>

