<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   `New Scandal' of Troops' Appearance Rocks Parliament </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101121794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1131 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2101121794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By BELINFORM for TASS] </F>
  [Text] Minsk January 21 TASS -- A new scandal rocked the 
Belarusian Parliament on Friday [21 January] and lawmakers gave 
an outline approval to a draft resolution demanding to sack the 
interior minister and the KGB head. 
  The scandal erupted after interior troops were sent close to 
the building where the parliamentary session is going on late on 
Thursday. Lawmaker Ivan Gerasyuk asked the parliament to clear 
up on whose orders the troops arrived. 
  "Without naming the concrete people who gave the order it is 
impossible to continue the work of the session," he said. 
  Parliament Speaker Stanislav Shushkevich said that troops 
appeared in full combat readiness in downtown city and this 
could have been sanctioned only by the prime minister. 
  Shushkevich also informed that he had called Interior 
Minister Vladimir Yegorov and instructed him that his first 
deputy -- interior troops Commander Konstantin Platonov -- 
appears in parliament. 
  Shushkevich recalled that when the current parliamentary 
session began interior and reinforced police units appeared on 
Independence Square as well. 
  This time the troops appeared after two days of 
parliamentary 
discussions about who allowed Lithuanian police to arrest two 
communist leaders of Lithuania on the territory of independent 
Belarus. 
  Mikolas Burokiavicius and Yuozas Jarmalavicius arrived in 
Minsk for a secret meeting of communist leaders of the three 
Baltic states, were arrested by Lithuanian police and taken to 
Vilnius. 

</TEXT>

