<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   General Cited on Missile Accord With U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2001213694 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 1930 GMT 
20 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2001213694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Slavyanka" program] </F>
  [Text] Russia's strategic missiles, which are on combat 
alert, will have a zero flight task. This was how Lieutenant 
General (Viktor Yesin), the head of the operational department 
of the main headquarters of strategic missile forces, explained 
the essence of the Russian-U.S. agreement on the nontargeting of 
their strategic missiles at one another. According to him, 
day-to-day control of nuclear weapons will be carried on the 
basis that Russia has no enemies as defined by the Russian 
military doctrine. At the same time, the general noted that 
under certain circumstances on orders from the Russian 
president, the supreme commander of the armed forces, targets 
could be introduced into the missiles' control system. This 
system still exists and the essence of a combat alert has not 
changed. 

</TEXT>

