<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Navy Concerned Over Ukraine's Action on Fleet </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK1901120094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 19 Jan 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> MK1901120094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Aleksandr Pilat report in the "Crimea" column: "The </F>
Situation Around the Black Sea Fleet Is Heating Up. Yet 
Commanders May Come to Agreement"] 
  [Excerpts] Recently Black Sea Fleet servicemen have often 
been showing their concern over the failure to resolve the Black 
Sea Fleet issue. [passage omitted] 
  In light of this the Black Sea Fleet Press Center has been 
authorized to make it known to personnel that documents have 
been submitted to the command indicating that the Russian Navy 
leadership shares the Black Sea Fleet servicemen's concern over 
the dragging out of the talks on the fleet's fate. The Russian 
Federation Navy Command has sent a telegram to the Ukrainian 
Defense Ministry pointing to the impermissibility of unilateral 
actions with respect to the Black Sea Fleet. 
  "The Russian Federation Navy Command is doing everything 
possible to ensure the implementation of the Massandra 
agreements whereby the Black Sea Fleet with its infrastructure 
is to pass under Russia's jurisdiction," the press center's 
release stresses. 
  Attention in being drawn to the fact that the Russian 
president has sent a letter to the Ukrainian president 
suggesting that a detailed investigation be held into the 
circumstances surrounding the death of Captain 1st Rank Andrey 
Lazebnikov, head of the Black Sea Fleet press center, and 
expressing concern over the deterioration of the crime situation 
in Sevastopol. 
  On 17 January a telephone conversation took place between 
Black Sea Fleet Acting Commander Vice Admiral Vitaliy Larionov 
(Black Sea Fleet commander Admiral Eduard Baltin is currently on 
vacation) and Vladimir Beskaravaynyy, commander of the Ukrainian 
Navy. The sides discussed the current state of relations 
between the two fleets, recognizing the impermissibility of 
unilateral actions prior to top- level decisions on the Black 
Sea Fleet being made. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

