<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Official Karasin Holds Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Advises Assessing Text of Kozyrev Speech </H4>
<F P=102> LD2001120994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1147 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2001120994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 20 TASS -- Spokesman of the Russian 
Foreign Ministry Grigoriy Karasin said it is impossible for 
foreign officials to react to the statements of the Russian 
foreign minister without even seeing the full text of his speech. 
  "The Russian foreign minister has given a detailed enough 
characteristic of the inadequate reaction of official 
representatives of foreign states, including the United States 
and the Baltics to his speech on January 18. It is hard to add 
anything to it, however, a logical question appears: How such 
hasty statements can be made even before their authors get 
acquainted with the full text of the minister's speech, how does 
this get into the framework of normal and generally-accepted 
norms of political communication", he told TASS on Thursday. 
  "Reporters of ITAR-TASS and other news agencies have wired 
only separate quotes taken out of the context and it is not 
their fault that such a sharp response followed. All these 
moments were rather fully characterised by the foreign minister 
on January 19. He expressed concern that someone has not got 
rid yet of the image of an enemy in the face of Russia or tries 
to restore it. In any case this unfortunate incident should be 
a good lesson", Karasin said. 
  Before Kozyrev's speech on Wednesday Karasin told INTERFAX 
news agency that TASS had misconstrued Kozyrev's comments. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

