<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Official Karasin Holds Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Reaction to Speech Causes `Indignation' </H4>
<F P=102> LD2001135494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1252 
GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2001135494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Boris Krivoshey and </F>
Aleksandr Krylovich] 
  [Text] Moscow, 20 Jan--"Incomprehension and indignation" 
has been provoked in Moscow by the official reaction in Latvia, 
Lithuania, and Estonia and a number of other countries to the 
statements of Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev at the 
conference of Russian ambassadors to CIS and Baltic countries on 
18 January, reaction which was based on a distorted 
interpretation of the minister's words. This was stated today 
at a briefing by Grigoriy Karasin, director of the Information 
and Press Department of the Russian Federation Ministry of 
Foreign Affairs. 
  He stressed that "without waiting for explanations about 
what 
the minister of foreign affairs was really saying, or at least 
for the full text of his speech, representatives of the U.S. 
Department of State and some Baltic states deemed it possible to 
make hasty and unfounded statements." 
  One gets the impression, the Russian Foreign Ministry 
spokesman noted, that "instead of concentrating on the 
continuation of constructive work to finalize the agreements and 
treaties that are now the subject of negotiation, our Baltic 
partners have lifted individual quotations out of context in 
order to attract world attention yet again and to try and gain 
certain political dividends from this." According to Karasin, 
"another aim of this maneuver is to whip up an artificial 
hullabaloo and avoid making decisions on how the rights of the 
Russian-speaking communities in Latvia and Estonia can be 
properly safeguarded." 
  "In our view, the West should also be concentrating 
attention 
on these problems rather than criticizing a Russian minister in 
the way that an official spokesman for the U.S. State Department 
allowed himself to do," Karasin declared. 
  According to the Russian representative, the heart of the 
matter was "explained at length by the Russian foreign minister 
during yesterday's television address, and then again in the 
closing stage of the conference. "We do not see any need for 
additional clarifications," Karasin concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

