<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Official Karasin Holds Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Yugoslav-Croatian Agreement Welcomed </H4>
<F P=102> LD2101045894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 0027 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2101045894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, Jan 20 (TANJUG) -- Russia welcomes the 
agreement reached between Yugoslavia and Croatia to start 
normalizing ties as a constructive element in the efforts aimed 
at breaking the deadlock in war-torn Bosnia-Herzegovina, a 
Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman said on Thursday. 
  The spokesman, Grigoriy Karasin, told reporters that the 
declaration could not only help stabilize Serb-Croat relations, 
but also have a positive effect on resolving the problem of 
Krajina (the state created by Serbs within the boundaries of the 
former Yugoslav republic of Croatia). 
  The foreign ministers of Yugoslavia and Croatia, Vladislav 
Jovanovic and Mate Granic, signed in Geneva on Wednesday a 
statement on the normalization of mutual relations and opening 
of representative offices in Belgrade and Zagreb on February 15. 
  Belgrade said on Thursday the statement did not imply mutual 
recognition and establishment of diplomatic ties between the two 
states and did not prejudge a solution to the problem existing 
between Croatia and the U.N.-protected Republic of Serb Krajina. 

</TEXT>

