<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin `Disappointed' With Geneva Talks on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2001085894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 2049 
GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2001085894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Konstantin Pribytkov] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, 19 Jan -- "I am very disappointed. Once 
again, as during the previous round in Geneva and Brussels, a 
great opportunity to reach agreement has been wasted." This is 
how Vitaliy Churkin, the Russian president's special 
representative and deputy minister of foreign affairs, assessed 
the outcome of the talks on a Bosnian settlement which ended 
here today, and which were attended by the delegations of the 
conflicting sides -- the Muslims, Serbians, and Croatians -- and 
the presidents of Serbia, Croatia, and Montenegro. Although 
co-chairmen Turvala Stoltenberg and David Owen proposed 
solutions and approaches which could be "satisfactory in order 
to stop the war," no compromise was achieved, the Russian 
diplomat noted, speaking to journalists in Geneva's Palais des 
Nations. 
  V. Churkin, who met the representatives of the various sides 
during his stay in Geneva, describes the agreement signed today 
between the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and Croatia on the 
opening of official missions in Belgrade and Zagreb as "an 
important step in their relations." It may lead to the 
emergence of "a more positive atmosphere for solving major 
issues," in particular the problem of Krajina. 

</TEXT>

