<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Belarus Aide on Ruble Zone, Economic Partnership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2001142594 Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA in Russian 20 Jan 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM2001142594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Vasiliy Ustyuzhanin report: "Don't Close Window Into </F>
Europe"] 
  [Text] It proved absolutely impossible to get hold of any 
Belarusian Supreme Soviet leader. They were all attending a 
session. Only the telephone of Aleksandr Sheleg, aide to the 
first deputy chairman of the Belarusian Supreme Soviet, was 
answered: "Our Prime Minister Kebich has long upheld the idea of 
a sound economic partnership. And his initiative for the 
republic to enter into a single ruble zone with Russia is 
consistent in this respect. After the breakup of the USSR 
Belarus effectively remains the sole window into Europe for 
Russia: The main air, railroad, and automobile routes and 
pipelines pass through it. We would not be a burden. Our 
flagships -- the tractor, automobile, and other plants -- are 
effectively standing idle now. And the same thing is happening 
in Russia. I am convinced that, if a decision were adopted -- 
and that is what our industrialists are waiting for -- things 
would return to life here. And I think Yeltsin realizes this." 
  It has become known that Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin 
will come to Minsk in the next few days. His visit may herald a 
definitive decision in favor of unifying the two republics' 
financial systems. 

</TEXT>

