<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dealer: 3 Russian Subs Sold </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101093194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0803 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2101093194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vasiliy Golovnin] </F>
  [Text] Tokyo January 21 TASS -- A Japanese mediator of the 
Russian-North Korean submarine deal dispelled fears of Tokyo and 
Seoul saying only three Russian decommissioned submarines 
without armaments had been sold to Pyongyang and had been 
scrapped there. 
  Ariyoshi Sibata, president of the Japanese company "Toen 
Shiozi", which mediated the deal told TASS on Friday by 
telephone from Beijing, where he is currently staying, that his 
company engages in trade in scrapped metal and therefore is 
interested in cooperation with Russia which has huge amounts of 
decommissioned machinery, including military equipment. 
  He rejected claims of U.S. mass media that Russia and North 
Korea had signed a deal envisaging shipments of a whole fleet 
consisting of 40 submarines which Pyongyang may use for training 
and as spare parts for its military equipment. 
  In October 1993 Sibata's company brokered a deal upon a 
North 
Korean request to ship three decommissioned and dismantled 
diesel submarines from the Russian Pacific Fleet to Pyongyang. 
  Sibata said the submarines had no armaments, were heavily 
covered with rust and were semi-submerged. The submarines had 
already been delivered to North Korea where they were cut into 
pieces 1x1.5 metres in size to be used as scrap metal, he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

