<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gromov Denies Reports of Sales </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101110794 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 0900 GMT 
21 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2101110794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Admiral Feliks Gromov, commander in chief of 
Russia's Navy, stated at a news conference in Vladivostok that 
Russia has not sold any submarines to North Korea and does not 
intend to sell any, the RIA agency reported. He said that four 
old, obsolete diesel submarines, which were incapable of moving 
under their own power, were sold as scrap to a Japanese 
commercial firm. Therefore, the fuss whipped up by the Japanese 
and South Korean media is totally groundless. 
  The Navy's commander in chief added that the press published 
another untrue report, of unknown provenance, that the Pacific 
Fleet is to supply 40 submarines to the DPRK via a dummy 
Japanese firm. The Pacific Fleet simply does not have this many 
old submarines, Feliks Gromov said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

