<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Envoy Explains Security Guarantees </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1901225694 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 2015 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1901225694 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kiev, [no date as received] -- At a meeting with 
journalists on 19 January, William Miller, the U.S. ambassador 
to Ukraine, explained his vision of ways of implementing the 
security guarantees given to Ukraine by the United States. "If 
any state carries out an attack on Ukraine or makes territorial 
claims on it, the United States will appeal to international 
organizations such as the United Nations in order to protect 
Ukraine," the U.S. ambassador noted. Talks on disarmament have 
been tense in recent months. Their participants concentrated 
special attention on three issues: Guarantees of Ukraine's 
security, the forms and amounts of compensation for enriched 
uranium contained in warheads, and the rendering of technical 
and economic assistance for the dismantlement of nuclear 
weapons. 
  Replying to questions from journalists, William Miller 
stressed that of the $800 million, which the United States will 
be granting for implementing the program of nuclear disarmament 
of Russia, Belarus, Kazakhstan, and Ukraine, our state will 
receive $175 million. The United States also pledged to give 
humanitarian and technical assistance to Ukraine. The 
ambassador reported that a Ukrainian delegation will be leaving 
for the United States next week, which would be engaged in 
issues of coordinating U.S. assistance to Ukraine. At the end 
of the meeting, William Miller expressed the hope that Russia 
and other UN member states would adhere to the charter of this 
organization. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

