<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Clinton Telephones Ulmanis </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101043994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0015 
GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2101043994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Kuchina] </F>
  [Text] Riga, 21 Jan -- On Thursday evening U.S. President 
Bill Clinton telephoned Latvian President Guntis Ulmanis. The 
head of the Baltic state reported on the late night television 
news, "Clinton categorically asserts that he differentiates 
between human rights, citizenship, and the question of the 
withdrawal of Russian troops." The army, said Clinton, must be 
withdrawn within the deadlines set without any kind of 
additional conditions. He spoke of his support for the troop 
withdrawal process and expressed the hope, according to Ulmanis, 
that Latvia will resolve the issues of human rights and 
citizenship in the spirit of the provisions of the CSCE. 
Clinton also stressed "that human rights and citizenship are 
the affair of each state, of each people." "I think," Ulmanis 
noted, "that this is very important for us." 
  During the conversation an exchange of comments took place 
on 
the recent utterances of Andrey Kozyrev. The view of the U.S. 
President, Ulmanis said, "allows Latvia to calm down somewhat." 
However, Ulmanis added, "we should always be prepared for such 
an aggressive policy." 
  According to Ulmanis, Clinton's telephone call "allowed us 
to 
dispel many of the suspicions regarding the talks between the 
United States and Russia." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-56959 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov014_g_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-014 </AU>
