<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Details Discussion on Removal of Shushkevich </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2001204994 Paris AFP in English 2031 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2001204994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Minsk, Jan 20 (AFP) -- The parliament of Belarus, 
elected during the Soviet era, voted Thursday [20 January] to 
discuss removing parliamentary speaker and head of state 
Stanislav Shushkevich from office, pro-reform deputy Leonid 
Loiko told AFP. 
  The deputies, of whom two-thirds were elected under 
communist 
colours in 1990, accused Shushkevich of contributing to the 
collapse of the Soviet Union in December 1991 and of delaying 
the return of Belarus to the ruble zone. 
  The closed-session debate on Shushkevich's future will take 
place on Friday, Loiko said. 
  Shushkevich was elected parliamentary speaker, and thus head 
of state, in September 1991, replacing the conservative Nikolay 
Dementey who resigned following the failure of a hardline coup 
attempt in Moscow the previous month. 
  Along with the Russian and Ukrainian presidents, Boris 
Yeltsin and Leonid Kravchuk, he signed an accord, prepared at 
Brest but known as the Minsk Agreement, in December 1991, 
declaring the end of the Soviet Union and the creation of the 
loosely constituted Commonwealth of Independent States. 
  The Belarus deputies also discussed the possible dismissal 
of 
Prime Minister Vyacheslav Kebich, Interior Minister Vladimir 
Yegorov, secret service chief Eduard Shirkovskiy and state 
prosecutor Vasiliy Sholodonov, the Baltic News Service reported. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

