<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japan To Discontinue Humanitarian </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2301071894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0659 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2301071894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vyacheslav Bantin] </F>
  [Text] Tokyo January 23 TASS -- Japan intends to stop 
giving humanitarian aid to Russia and to monitor the 
effectiveness of other programmes for assistance to Moscow, 
according to a Japanese Government decision to revise the policy 
of assistance to Russia, a number of central Japanese newspapers 
reported on Sunday referring to sources in the country's Foreign 
Ministry. 
  According to the sources, Tokyo has arrived at a conclusion 
about the need to give up implementing the earlier announced 
humanitarian aid programmes, worth a total of 500 million U.S. 
dollars, considering the internal political situation in Russia. 
  Tokyo believes that the implementation of humanitarian aid 
programmes now may only be detrimental to the administration of 
President Boris Yeltsin, because, in the light of mounting 
nationalist and great-power sentiments in Russia, the Russian 
Government has been increasingly criticised for accepting 
foreign humanitarian aid. 
  Still, Tokyo intends to carry out all the other programmes 
for assistance to Russia in keeping with its commitments but 
will also monitor the effectiveness of their realisation. 
  Japanese Foreign Ministry sources emphasise that it is 
planned to attach paramount importance, first of all, to those 
programmes which actually promote radical economic reforms and 
help moscow take measures necessary to build a market economy. 
  Tokyo came to a conclusion about the need for such an 
approach in view of the formation of a new Russian Government 
which plans to introduce changes to the previously pursued 
economic policy, and with due regard for the results of the 
December elections to Russia's new parliament. 
  The Japanese Government intends to call on other western 
countries to reconsider their programme for assistance to Moscow 
so that they would stimulate Russia's headway along the road of 
reforms to a greater extent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

