<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japan Refutes Aid Rumor </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401060794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0248 
GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2401060794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS correspondent Vasiliy Golovnin] </F>
  [Text] Tokyo, 24 Jan -- Today a representative of the 
Japanese Foreign Affairs Ministry called the reports that 
appeared in the press about Tokyo deciding to stop humanitarian 
aid to Russia "a lie." On Sunday a number of Japanese 
newspapers, citing anonymous sources in the country's Foreign 
Affairs Ministry, informed that such a step was seemingly 
connected with the fact that the Russian population was having 
an increasingly negative attitude to "sops from abroad." 
  In a talk with an ITAR-TASS correspondent, a representative 
of the department on questions of aid to new independent states 
of the Japanese Foreign Affairs Ministry stated that such 
reports in no way corresponded to the facts. According to him, 
no changes had been made in the programs of aid to Russia, and 
they were all being consistently carried out at working level. 
This is also true in full for humanitarian aid to the former 
USSR, for which Tokyo has alloted $100,000,000, mainly to 
provide medicines. 
  The Foreign Affairs Ministry representative called the 
recently announced auction for Japanese companies to gain the 
right to supply consumer goods to Russia within the framework of 
the humanitarian aid program evidence of Japan's consecutive 
efforts in this direction. 

</TEXT>

