<H3> <TI>   Japan To Urge Full Troop Withdrawal From South Kurils </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2301120794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1145 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2301120794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vyacheslav Bantin] </F>
  [Text] Tokyo January 23 TASS -- During the forthcoming 
Russian-Japanese talks between representatives of the command of 
the armed forces of the two countries, to be held here at the 
beginning of February, the Japanese side intends to demand 
complete withdrawal of Russian troops from South Kurils, which 
Tokyo lays claim to. A final decision to hold such talks was 
taken by the Japanese government on Saturday, the newspaper 
SEKAI NIPPO reported on Sunday. 
  Representatives of the command of the Russian Armed Forces 
are to arrive in Tokyo to attend a two-day seminar for the 
military and experts from Russia, the United States, and Japan 
on security in the northern Pacific. The seminar opens on 
February 1. Immediately after the seminar, the two sides will 
hold talks. 
  The Russian side intends to suggest setting about taking 
measures to build confidence between the two countries in the 
military field. In particular, Moscow will suggest implementing 
a programme for exchanges of servicemen and mutual friendship 
visits of the navy ships of the two countries. 
  The Japanese military, according to the newspaper, are 
planning to urge Moscow to demilitarise the South Kurils as soon 
as possible and provide Tokyo with full information concerning 
the potential of the armed forces and defence construction in 
Russia's Far East. 

</TEXT>

