<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lukin Opposes NATO Plans for Former Yugoslavia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101164994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1505 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2101164994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: by diplomatic </F>
correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboinikov, Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy 
Trubetskoy and others] 
  [Text] The Chairman of the State Duma Committee on Foreign 
Affairs, Vladimir Lukin, has addressed to the Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev a formal request for the package of international 
treaties and other acts, subject to parliamentary ratification. 
  He told INTERFAX on Friday [21 January] that he had asked 
the 
minister to set priorities on the documents' review. 
  In line with the federal Constitution, the Duma endorses the 
appointment and the calling of Russia's ambassadors. For this 
reason, Lukin also asked Kozyrev to spell out his suggestions on 
this score, too. 
  Russia's ambassador to the U.S. before his election to the 
Duma, Lukin explained that formally he was still ambassador, 
even though he had sent a letter of resignation to President 
Yeltsin. 
  He reported that his committee had held its first session on 
Thursday. "We know what to do, but we don't know where to do it 
since up until now we've had no premises to house the 
committee," Lukin said. 
  He said that he had initiated parliamentary debates on the 
situation in the former Yugoslavia and had drafted an 
appropriate statement. 
  An alternative draft on the Yugoslav crisis, according to 
Lukin, had been prepared by three factions -- the Communists, 
Agrarians, and Liberal-Democrats. 
  Lukin voiced "grave concern" over NATO's persistent 
discussions on the possibility of hitting targets in the former 
Yugoslavia. 
  The document notes that force will hardly end the war there 
but will only aggravate the conflict. 
  In Lukin's opinion, the Duma should urge the president and 
government "to spare no effort to avoid the escalation of 
fighting in the former Yugoslavia." 
  In the alternative draft, the Communists, Agrarians, and 
Liberal- Democrats describe as "inadmissible any coercive 
measure against the former Yugoslav republics, including the 
establishment of no-fly zones." 
  The Russian side is requested to adopt "appropriate 
measures" 
within the framework of the UN Security Council "for getting 
these recommendations implemented." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

