<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Criticizes Opponents of Arms Treaty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101180894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1703 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2101180894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian leader Leonid Kravchuk says "those who 
offer Ukraine to hold back to its nuclear arsenal want the 
country to become hostage to the nuclear weapons signing a death 
warrant to the people of Ukraine". He was speaking in Kiev on 
Friday [21 January] while attending the national stock exchange. 
  Kravchuk said that by signing the three-nation nuclear 
disarmament agreement in Moscow, "we have met the conditions set 
by the Ukrainian parliament during the ratification of the 
Start-1 agreement." He said the government embarked on the road 
of implementing rather than blocking parliamentary resolutions 
and had to strike compromise and make concessions as it should 
be. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

