<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kazakhstan's Nazarbayev Urges Economic Ties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101204794 Kiev UT-1 Television Network in Ukrainian 1900 
GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2101204794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UT-1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] Nursultan Nazarbayev was warmly 
welcomed everywhere by Dnepropetrovsk oblast residents. 
  [Begin Nazarbayev recording, in Russian] During our 
negotiations with President Leonid Makarovych Kravchuk in Kiev 
yesterday, and during our conversation with chairman of the 
Dnepropetrovsk oblast administration Pavlo Ivanovych 
[Lazarenko], we were saying how greatly our economic ties have 
diminished in these past few years! Last year alone, the trade 
turnover between Russia and Kazakhstan amounted to 1.650 billion 
dollars. Experts believe it should equal 5 or 6 billion. 
  Kazakhstan used to have terrific ties with Dnepropetrovsk 
oblast alone, and now they are reduced by 50 percent. What does 
it mean? No goods are supplied to Kazakhstan while people are 
losing jobs here. When no relevant products are supplied to us, 
we are unable to launch a certain production line. Everybody 
loses in the long run. 
  Now that we have recovered from euphoria and grasped the 
situation, we must gradually set up horizontal ties. We must 
all now think how we can bring people together, how we can lift 
the border barriers, how we can establish freedom of movement, 
and how we can help each other's economies find their feet 
again? [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

