<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Service Chief Views Crimea Situation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401075894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0725 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2401075894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Yefim Shvartsman] </F>
  [Text] Kiev January 24 TASS -- The Ukrainian leadership is 
seriously concerned over the character of political 
confrontation in the Crimea following the first round of 
presidential elections there on January 16. This anxiety was 
expressed in the Sunday analytical programme Perekryostok 
(Crossroads) of Ukrainian TV. 
  Perekryostok reminded people once again of the right, 
granted 
to President Kravchuk by the Supreme Soviet (parliament) of 
Ukraine, to cancel resolutions of local government authorities 
running counter to the Ukrainian constitution (in the opinion of 
observers, the presidential elections in the Crimea are just the 
case), and gave the floor to Yevgeniy Marchuk, head of the 
Ukrainian security service. He described the situation as 
criminally dangerous and urged the rivals to act within the 
limits set by the law. 
  Taking into account the polarization of opinions in the 
Crimea itself over the future of the peninsula before the second 
round of the presidential elections, scheduled for January 30, 
as well as the fact that two obviously political assassinations 
took place in the Crimea over the past month (Captain Andrey 
Lazebnikov, head of the press service of the Black Sea Fleet, 
was killed in Sevastopol last December and Iskander Mamedov, 
deputy to the Crimean parliament from the Crimean Tatars, died 
of wounds in Simferopol last Friday, following an attempt on his 
life), one cannot but agree that the concern of the head of the 
Ukrainian security service is well-grounded and his warning is 
timely. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

