<H3> <TI>   Crimea Supreme Council Presidium Issues Appeal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101162094 Kiev UNIAR in Ukrainian 2210 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2101162094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Simferopol, 20 January -- The Crimean Supreme 
Council Presidium has appealed to the peninsula's population in 
connection with the Day of the Republic of the Crimea. It is 
said in the appeal, in particular, that in the time that has 
passed (since gaining autonomy) the course taken toward the 
Crimea gradually attaining statehood has proved to be right. 
"With the interests of all the peoples populating the Crimea 
taken into consideration, a possibility for the Crimea to become 
a bridge uniting Russia and Ukraine, with and peace and civic 
accord on the peninsula preserved and not undermined, the will 
of the Crimeans, has been realized. Recreating the republic, 
adopting its own constitution, delimiting powers between itself 
and Ukraine, and signing economic agreements are all difficult 
but necessary means of creating preconditions for the Crimea to 
be economically independent. The elections of the president and 
Supreme Council of the Crimea will complete this rather short 
but important stage in the history of the Crimea. The future 
destiny of the republic is in the hands of the Crimeans 
themselves," the statement notes. 

</TEXT>

