<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Republicans Threaten To Appeal to UN </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101182694 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 1450 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2101182694 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sevastopol -- The coordinating council of the city 
branch of the Republican Party of Crimea [RPK] sent a statement 
to the presidents and parliaments of Russia and Ukraine on 21 
January saying: "The outcome of the first round of presidential 
elections in the Republic of Crimea revealed the real balance of 
political forces which took shape as a result of the Ukrainian 
Government's antipopular policy based on unitarianism and 
nationalism." The statement also stresses that the presidential 
elections pose no contradiction to Ukraine's laws and 
constitution and are held in full compliance with the law "On 
division of powers between the Republic of Crimea and Ukraine." 
In the Republicans' opinion, this was also confirmed by 
Ukraine's Ministry of Justice in reply to a query whether 
Sevastopol had the right to take part in these elections. 
  The Sevastopol branch of the RPK said that the measures 
taken 
by the government and president of Ukraine to restrict Crimea's 
powers and the rights of the people of the autonomous republic 
may become the last straw which will spark off a big fire. If 
the Crimean people, who will be electing their president, see 
the expression of their will ignored, "we will have to appeal to 
the world community, specifically, to the United Nations," the 
statement says. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

