<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimea's Meshkov Interviewed on Election </TI></H3>
<H4>   Views Black Sea Fleet Situation </H4>
<F P=102> LD2101224794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1749 
GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2101224794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Mikhail Shevtsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 21 Jan -- "The decision for the Black Sea 
Fleet to remain Russian--and it must be fully implemented--does 
not raise any doubts," Yuriy Meshkov, candidate for the 
presidency of Crimea and leader of the Republican Party of 
Crimea, said in an exclusive interview with ITAR-TASS today. 
  The leader of the Crimean Republicans, who won approximately 
40 percent of the votes in the first round of the presidential 
elections, while speaking in favor of an independent Republic of 
Crimea "which would maintain multi-faceted ties with Ukraine 
and, independently of these ties, would determine the forms of 
economic relations with Russia," thought that the sympathies of 
the population of the peninsula are on the side of the "Russia" 
opposition bloc which he represents. Yuriy Meshkov pointed out 
that the rest of the votes were distributed between the 
supporters of the Communist and Russia Parties. He noted that 
"not a single external force is capable of upsetting our 
progress toward closer relations with the republics of the 
former USSR and uniting the Russian and Ukrainian peoples." 
Yuriy Meshkov is convinced that his voters would be able to 
consolidate their positions in the second round of the elections 
and ensure a victory in the presidential race for the leader of 
the Crimean republicans. 
  Replying to the ITAR-TASS correspondent's question about the 
reasons behind the increase in crime in Crimea since the murder 
of Andrey Lazebnikov, head of the Black Sea Fleet's press 
service at the end of 1993, Yuriy Meshkov said that these "are 
the consequences of the full atrophy of the present Crimean 
leadership and its inability to maintain law and order in the 
region." In the event of his victory in the presidential 
elections the leader of the Crimean republicans promises "to 
establish order and eliminate organized crime in the peninsula." 
  In Yuriy Meshkov's view, the implementation of the 
tripartite 
agreement on the elimination of nuclear weapons in Ukraine 
signed in Moscow on 14 January by the presidents of Russia, the 
United States, and Ukraine, would make it possible "to 
significantly reduce tension in the world and contribute to 
strengthening nuclear security throughout the world." 
  Commenting on the removal of Ivan Yermakov from the post of 
the Ukrainian president's representative in Sevastopol, Yuriy 
Meshkov told the ITAR-TASS correspondent that this decision was 
made by the Ukrainian leadership "out of political motives." At 
the same time, he noted, "Yermakov who has been enrolled in the 
staff of the Black Sea Fleet, should be proud of this 
appointment." It is known that Admiral Eduard Baltin, commander 
of the fleet, issued an order on 20 December enrolling under his 
command the former representative of the Ukrainian president in 
Crimea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

