<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   KGB Denies Involvement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1901222294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 2022 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1901222294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Eduard Shirkovsky, Chairman of the Belarussian KGB, 
told a closed session of the country's Supreme Soviet that 
Mikolas Burokevicius and Juozas Jermalavicius, leaders of the 
banned Communist Party of Lithuania (CPSU), had been kidnapped 
in Minsk by two Lithuanian policemen with the aid of the 
Belarusian Interior Ministry, not by the Lithuanian security 
service. 
  The KGB chief said that this "act of international 
gangsterism" was possible because the KGB did not control the 
activities of the Interior Ministry. 
  Vladimir Yegorov, the Interior Minister, told parliament 
that 
officers of the Belarusian Interior Ministry detained the two 
men in the presence of two Lithuanian law enforcement officers. 
He said that the Belarusian police did not have a written 
arrest warrant but this action had been discussed by Interior 
Ministry and prosecution officers, in particular by the interior 
minister and the prosecutor general of Belarus. 
  In Yegorov's words, the men involved in the detention 
believed that an arrest warrant did exist, which is why the car 
carrying the Lithuanian special service men and the detainees 
left for the Belarusian-Lithuanian border. 
  Pyotr Kravchenko, Belarusian Foreign Minister, said that his 
ministry had not received any messages that were required by the 
appropriate agreement between Belarus and Lithuania about the 
arrest. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

