<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze, Mitterrand Comment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101235294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 2043 
GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2101235294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspodent Sergey Batyrev] </F>
  [Text] Paris, 21 Jan -- The signing of a treaty on accord, 
friendship and cooperation between France and Georgia and the 
meeting between Georgian head of state Eduard Shevardnadze and 
French President Francois Mitterrand were the most important 
moments of the final day of the Georgian leader's visit to 
France. 
  After a prolonged conversation between the two countries' 
leaders in the Elysee Palace there was a ceremonial signing of 
the French-Georgian treaty, which will create the legal 
framework for the future relations of cooperation between the 
two countries. After this, Eduard Shevardnadze signed on 
Georgia's behalf the Paris Charter for a New Europe - the basic 
document of the Conference for Security and Cooperation in 
Europe, marking the end of the Cold War and proclaiming the 
principle of the settlement of all conflicts by peaceful means. 
  The conclusion of the treaty between France and Georgia 
means 
that we are establishing special relations of cooperation and 
interaction between us, Francois Mitterrand said at the signing 
ceremony. Today Georgia is encountering significant 
difficulties of a political and economic nature, and it can 
count on the solidarity of its friends, the French president 
noted. We face interaction in Europe, which is now being built 
anew, and both our countries bear responsibility for the success 
of this, the French head of state said. 
  The signing of today's documents represents a historic 
moment 
for Georgia, Eduard Shevardnadze said in his reply. Today we 
are going through a difficult period, but I believe in Georgia's 
future, and it is linked above all with the fact that we have 
friends in the world, the Georgian leader said. We arrived in 
Paris with great hopes, and I must say that these hopes have 
come true. Today we are opening a new page in the relations 
between our countries, the head of the Republic of Georgia said. 
  Eduard Shevardnadze summed up the initial results of his 
visit to France at a news conference today. The main aims of 
the visit are to establish normal relations with France and 
discuss the most important political problems with its leader, 
and these have been achieved, he said. France, he remarked, has 
promised aid for Georgia in various fields, including by taking 
an active role with Russia, the United States and Germany in the 
work by states friendly to Georgia to find a way of resolving 
the Abkhazia conflict. 
  Georgia is placing particular emphasis on developing 
relations with Russia, Eduard Shevardnadze said. He stressed 
that there are high hopes in his country for the visit to 
Tbilisi by President Yeltsin, scheduled for early February. I 
hope that these hopes are justified, he said. 
  I spent much time with my French counterpart discussing the 
new Russia and its new role in the world, meaning in the 
post-communist period, Eduard Shevardnadze remarked in reply to 
a question from ITAR-TASS. We noted that this role can only be 
performed if Russia takes a democratic path, he commented. We 
believe the adoption of a new Russian constitution to be a 
significant event and attach great importance to the part that 
the country's presidency can play in guaranteeing democracy, the 
Georgian head of state said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

