<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze Comments Further </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2201235094 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 2200 GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2201235094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Novosti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] [Announcer] Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze 
today ended his official visit to France and returned to 
Tbilisi. In his first interview after arrival, Eduard 
Shevardnadze told journalists that realistic ways for a peaceful 
settlement of the crisis had taken shape at the talks between 
Georgia and Abkhazia that are under way in Geneva. 
  [Begin recording] [Shevardnadze] The main aim has been 
achieved, I mean the elaboration of a legal basis for 
cooperation and friendship between the two states [France and 
Georgia]. A large treaty was signed, and the prospects for 
economic relations look good. There was much talk, of course, 
about the state of things in Russia which is our concern and 
worry, too. The world community must support the democratic 
choice made by the whole of Russia and its president. 
  [Correspondent] Touching upon the prospects for relations 
between Georgia, UNESCO, and the Organization for Economic 
Cooperation and Development, Eduard Shevardnadze had the 
following to say: 
  [Shevardnadze] This work has just started. The 
status...[pauses] I have visited the headquarters of this 
organization and it seems to me that the prospects here are also 
good. We have agreed that a special delegation will visit (?us) 
and we will sort things out on the spot. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

