<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Treaty Concluded With Armenian Procurator </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2301175494 Tbilisi SAKARTVELOS RESPUBLIKA in Georgian 11 
Jan 94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> AU2301175494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi SAKARTVELOS RESPUBLIKA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Georgian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report from the press service of the Republic of Georgia </F>
Procurator's Office: "Georgia-Armenia: A Treaty Has Been Drawn 
Up"] 
  [Text] A treaty on mutual legal assistance has been signed 
in Tbilisi and Yerevan between the procurator's offices of the 
Republics of Georgia and Armenia. 
  "This treaty has particular importance for both sovereign 
countries," stated Jamlet Babilashvili, Republic of Georgia 
acting procurator general. "It will promote the joint efforts 
of the law enforcement bodies of the neighboring states in the 
struggle against organized crime, in particular terrorism, the 
narcotics business, and so forth; it will contribute to the 
successful fulfillment of supervisory functions connected with 
investigations, the arrest and transfer of criminals, and the 
resolution of other important questions." 
  Armenia is the seventh country with whose procurator's 
office 
Georgia's Procurator's Office has drawn up a treaty. Such 
treaties have been concluded with the Russian Federation, 
Ukraine, Kazakhstan, Turkmenistan, and other republics. 
Treaties are being prepared with the procurator's offices of 
Turkey, Bulgaria, Azerbaijan, Iran, and Afghanistan and they 
will soon become official. In short, Georgia's Procurator's 
Office is gaining international recognition on a broad scale. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

