<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Georgia, Abkhazia Urge Deployment of UN Troops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2201092694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0825 GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2201092694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Sitnikov] </F>
  [Text] United Nations Organisation January 22 TASS -- 
Georgia and Abkhazia are urging the deployment of the U.N. 
peace-keeping force in the conflict zone and are expressing 
their "mutual desire that the Russian military contingent should 
be included in it," says a communique on the results of the 
second round of the Geneva talks about the settlement of the 
Georgian-Abkhazian conflict, which was circulated here on Friday 
as a document of the Security Council. 
  According to the communique, "the sides will withdraw all 
armed units with arms and military hardware from the Inguri 
river and other possible lines of active confrontation within 
five days after the arrival of the peace-keeping force.... At 
the same time, international observers and peace-keeping troops 
will move into the areas from which armed units are withdrawn." 
  The communique pointed out that both the Georgian and 
Abkhazian sides "have recognised that the main task is to 
achieve a full-scale political settlement of the conflict, and 
all efforts should be concentrated on attaining this goal." 
They agreed to continue the discussion of the problem of 
Abkhazia's political status, taking into account the interests 
of both sides. The next meeting of experts on this issue will 
be held in Moscow on February 8. 
  Following the adoption of the Geneva communique, Georgia 
asked to convene the Security Council for discussing a 
possibility of sending a U.N. peace-keeping force to the area of 
the Georgian-Abkhazian conflict. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

