<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Abkhaz Officials Skeptical </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2301172194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1311 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2301172194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Leader of the Liberation of Abkhazia pressure group 
Boris Kakubava says that a military option is the only way of 
ensuring the return of refugees to Abkhazia. 
  In an interview with Interfax news agency on Sunday, he gave 
a highly negative response to the outcome of the Geneva talks 
between Georgia and Abkhazia including the problem of Georgian 
refugees. In his view, Russia cannot act as mediator because of 
Moscow's role in the conflict leading to the loss of Abkhazia. 
  Chairman of the national security and defence commission 
Nodar Natadze was likewise sceptical about the Geneva talks. 
The deployment of Russian troops along the Inguri river 
separating Georgia and Abkhazia as asked by the negotiating 
teams will prevent Georgians from crossing it and turn 
Abkhazia's Georgian population into slaves or hostages, he told 
Interfax. 
  Natadze says, "if Russia is really keen to see Georgia as a 
stable and integral state, it ought to deploy troops not along 
the Inguri but Psou river on Russia's border with Abkhazia". 

</TEXT>

