<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101100394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0923 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2101100394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Nikolay Sorokin] </F>
  [Text] Kazan January 21 TASS -- "There were and there are 
no problems between the Russian and Tatar interior ministries," 
Russian Interior Minister Viktor Yerin told a news conference in 
Kazan on Friday. All efforts by national extremists to drive a 
wedge between Russia and Tatarstan are in vain, the minister 
added. 
  In the minister's opinion, everything should be done in a 
civilised way. A government decision between Russia and 
Tatarstan is being drafted now. It will define ways of 
delegating powers. 
  All this is being made to reform the Russian Interior 
Ministry. The first move has been made: The role of city and 
district militia departments was increased. Their powers were 
enlarged. 
  These departments were granted additional rights and, 
consequently, their duties were increased. Functions which city 
and district departments are unable to fulfill, are delegated to 
regional departments or the Interior Ministry. The entire 
ministry will be remade on such principles. 
  Yerin noted that he gave a news conference on last year's 
results for the first time. Although the crime situation 
remains difficult, there are some positive changes. Crime rate 
rose by 1.4 per cent over the past year, while in 1992 it was 24 
per cent. 
  The rate of crime exposure is at the level of 50.6 per cent 
and for serious crimes -- 55.6 per cent. 
  The situation in Tatarstan is much better, the minister 
stressed. The general rate of crime exposure here is 60 per 
cent. The minister attributed this to special crime control 
measures taken by the republic for the second year running. 
  These measures should be thoroughly studied, the minister 
noted. In Yerin's opinion, Tatarstan outstripped Russian law 
enforcement bodies in taking initiatives in the sphere of crime 
control, which should be acclaimed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

