<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Assembly in Tallinn Appeals to Leaders </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2001145894 Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network in Estonian 1300 
GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2001145894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Estonian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Russian Representative Assembly has appealed to 
the Russian and U.S. Presidents for help with ending the 
continuing discrimination of Estonian inhabitants on the basis 
of their citizenship. An aggressive nationalist policy aimed at 
establishing a nation state, which manifests itself through a 
well-considered system of legislative acts, is directed toward 
ousting the Russian-language population from Estonia and brings 
them humiliation and suffering. This is what the appeal adopted 
at the session of the Representative Assembly's presidium on 18 
January says. 
  The appeal states that over a third of permanent Estonian 
residents have been declared to be foreigners; the principles of 
the Human Right Declaration and the Convention on the 
Elimination or Reduction of Statelessness have thereby been 
ignored. The Representative Assembly notes that until now the 
awarding of citizenship on the basis of one's free will has not 
been decided, as had been envisaged in the agreement on the 
foundations of interstate relations concluded between Estonia 
and Russia on 12 January 1991, as well as the granting of 
permits for permanent residence. This is what the 
Representative Assembly's statement says. 

</TEXT>

