<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials: Country May Be First To Sign NATO Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2101211494 Tallinn BNS in English 1932 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2101211494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, Jan 21, AP - BNS -- Lithuania will most 
likely become the first East European country to sign up next 
week for NATO's new plan granting limited partnerships to its 
former adversaries, officials said Friday [21 January]. 
  Lithuanian President Algirdas Brazauskas was scheduled to 
sign the "Partnership for Peace" document during a visit next 
Thursday to the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization. 
  At a recent summit, President Clinton and other alliance 
leaders invited their Warsaw Pact foes to accept the plan, which 
would draw the nations closer but without granting them 
membership. 
  NATO officials said the East Europeans can begin signing the 
partnership document on Monday. 
  After they do, they will work out individual programs for 
taking part in military exercises, peacekeeping and other NATO 
activities. In turn, the nations will have to share information 
about defense budgets, promise civilian control over the 
military and standardize weapons systems. 
  Lithuania earlier this month became the first former Soviet 
republic to ask for membership in the alliance and the security 
guarantees that would go with it. Poland, Hungary and others 
also want to join. 
  But the allies have refused to admit the East Europeans, 
fearing to do so would create a new divide in Europe and isolate 
and upset Russia, a formidable military power. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

