<H3> <TI>   Conservatives Worried Over International Security </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2201141894 Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network in Russian 1300 
GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2201141894 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The political council of the Homeland Union has made 
public a statement on further steps in the consolidation of 
Lithuania's international security. The conservatives state 
that after Lithuania's official statement on its intention to 
join NATO, new steps will undoubtedly be taken. As Russia's 
foreign policy toward the Baltic states is becoming ever more 
aggressive, the political council of the party of conservatives 
believes that during the upcoming visit by Lithuanian President 
Algirdas Brazauskas to Brussels and the signing of the document 
on cooperation for peace, the president should ask for 
consultations with NATO, provided by this document to Lithuania, 
as a partner who is facing direct threat to its territorial 
integrity, political independence, and security. 
  The political council of the party of conservatives is 
convinced that the NATO political consultants and observers 
should be working in Vilnius. 

</TEXT>

