<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Czech Minister Baudys Comments on Visit, Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1901151894 Vilnius Radio Vilnius in English 2230 GMT 18 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1901151894 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius Radio Vilnius </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] The minister of defense of the Czech 
Republic, Antonin Baudys, and the delegation headed by him began 
a visit to Lithuania on Monday. The report that follows was 
filed by Jonas Kernigis of the Lithuanian service of Radio 
Vilnius. 
  [Kernigis] The Czech defense minister was met at Vilnius 
airport by his Lithuanian counterpart, Linas Linkevicius, and 
other top-ranking military officials of the Ministry of Defense 
of the Republic of Lithuania. 
  The defense ministers of the two states had an exchange of 
opinion on bilateral cooperation between the Czech Republic and 
Lithuania. According to the Czech defense minister, Antonin 
Baudys, his country can sell Lithuania arms, if Lithuania 
expresses such a wish. Mr. Antonin Baudys said that the 
situation in Europe was complicated, following the 
disintegration of the Soviet Union, and owing to the unending 
military conflict in the Balkans. The war actions in the 
Balkans make NATO be cautious about admitting post-communist 
states to the organization. The Czech minister of defense, Mr. 
Antonin Baudys: 
  [Begin Baudys recording in Czech, fading to English 
translation] The government of the Czech Republic considered the 
issue of NATO membership all through the year 1993. Therefore 
the American Partnership for Peace initiative did not surprise 
us. We realised that this is the maximum that can be achieved 
in Europe. We were the first to approve the project. We 
understand that NATO must treat Russia as an economic and 
military partner. [end recording] 
  [Announcer] According to the Czech minister of defense, the 
Visegrad states, namely Poland, the Czech Republic, Slovakia and 
Hungary, as well as other East European states, seek NATO 
membership, striving to ground [as heard] that cooperation on a 
democratic state system and market economy. The Czech Republic 
also speaks up for the preservation of the existing state 
borders in Europe, and against the formation of any new military 
blocs on the continent. According to the Czech defense 
minister, the U.S. Partnership for Peace project makes it 
possible to put into practice the potential of East and Central 
European states, without doing harm to the peculiar interests of 
a given country. 
  According to the Czech minister of defense, Antonin Baudys, 
it was accentuated during the visit of the American President 
that the Partnership for Peace initiative did not only mean 
cooperation in the military sphere: 
  [Begin Baudys recording] The words uttered by the U.S. 
President during the visit to the Czech Republic witnessed that 
the United States will support European states by way of 
economic programs and investment. A draft of such cooperation 
has already been worked out and it will soon be submitted to the 
Czech Government. [end recording] 
  [Announcer] According to the Czech defense minister, each 
East European state must draw up its individual program of 
participation in the Partnership for Peace project. Lithuanian 
minister of national defense, Linas Linkevicius, told Radio 
Vilnius that new links of partnership with the Czech Republic 
were going to be established. 
  [Begin Linkevicius recording] Five groups of Lithuanian 
officers will go to the Czech Republic to gain experience there. 
At present, deputy minister of defense and the commander of the 
Air Force are having a course in that country, too. We expect 
Czech assistance in the sphere of armament development. 
Cooperation between the two states is concrete and fruitful, 
and that is most important. [end recording] 
  [Announcer] The defense minister of the Czech Republic will 
stay in Lithuania until Wednesday. The official visit of the 
Czech minister envisages meetings with Lithuanian President 
Algirdas Brazauskas and chairman of parliament, Ceslovas 
Jursenas. He will also visit units of the Lithuanian Army in 
Vilnius, Kaunas and Siauliai. 

</TEXT>

