<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fellow Party Members Clamp Down on Minister </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2101202394 Tallinn BNS in English 1632 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2101202394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jan 21, BNS -- Lithuanian Defense Minister 
Linas Linkevicius came under severe criticism of the ruling 
Lithuanian Democratic Labor Party [LDLP] faction for a number of 
unsolved problems in the system of national defense. 
  Linkevicius, who is a member of the LDLP faction himself, 
was 
appointed as defense minister last fall on the recommendation of 
his faction. 
  On Thursday [20 January], the board of the LDLP faction 
invited Linkevicius for a discussion. MP Arvydas Ivaskevicus, 
member of the parliament's National Security Committee, called 
Linkevicius' attention to "machinations" of high-ranking Defense 
Ministry officials. The lawmaker said he obtained information 
that the ministry unlawfully rents military facilities to 
commercial structures. 
  The meeting's participants said they are concerned about a 
high death and injury rate in the Armed Forces. "The Lithuanian 
Army is a smaller model of the Soviet Army," Ivaskevicius said. 
  MP Vytautas Petkevicius, chairman of the National Security 
Committee, said he is completely unsatisfied with the national 
defense reorganization plan that was submitted to the president 
behind the committee's back. 

</TEXT>

