<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ruling Party Faction Approaches Split </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2001202194 Tallinn BNS in English 1619 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2001202194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jan 20, BNS -- Lithuania's Future Forum 
will soon register its faction in the Lithuanian parliament, MP 
[member of parliament] Aleksandras Bendinskas told reporters 
Thursday [20 January]. 
  Bendinskas, who is a member of the forum, said the matter 
will be decided by all representatives of the organization in 
parliament. The forum participated in parliamentary elections on 
the list of Lithuanian Democratic Labor Party [LDLP]. In 
Bendinskas' words, the forum currently holds 22 seats. 
  A possibility to form a new faction appeared when the 
parliament amended its statute and allowed to create faction 
regardless of affiliation in pre-election lists. 
  Up until now, the ruling LDLP faction had 71 seats and 
enjoyed an absolute majority. If it loses 22 members, as well 
several others who intend to leave it during faction 
reregistration, the ruling faction will become almost equal to 
the rightist opposition coalition in size. There is a 
possibility, however, that the ruling majority will remain as 
unified as earlier when dealing with key issues. 

</TEXT>

