<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Law on Income Declaration by Officials Rejected </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2101202694 Tallinn BNS in English 1401 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2101202694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jan 21, BNS -- The Lithuanian parliament 
bowed to the president's veto that was put on the law on income 
declaration by officials and civil servants. The law was 
rejected during repeat consideration Thursday [20 January] by a 
53-13 vote, with 34 abstentions. 
  The abstentions virtually determined that the president's 
veto would come into effect. 71 votes were needed to approve 
the law repeatedly. In such case, the president's would have to 
sign the law and to promulgate it within three days. 
  During debates, a majority of lawmakers said the problem of 
income declaration by officials should be referred to the 
Constitutional Court. 
  President Algirdas Brazauskas sent the law back to the 
parliament for reconsideration because, in his opinion, some 
portions of the law contradict the constitutional principles of 
property inviolability and equality before the law. 
  The law was first adopted Dec. 23 under pressure of the 
rightist opposition. The law set two deadlines for income 
declaration by officials - May 1, 1994 for property owned prior 
to Feb. 1, 1994 and March 1, 1995 for property acquired in 1994. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

