<H3> <TI>   Return To Dedicated Parliamentary TV `Impossible' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2401112794 Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA in Russian 22 Jan 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM2401112794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Stas Stremidlovskiy report: "This `Hour' Will Not Solve Our </F>
Problems"] 
  [Text] It would seem that the "Parliamentary Hour" 
broadcast had died a sudden death, but... Yesterday morning at 
the request of Deputy Marychev (from the Liberal Democratic 
Party of Russia), the question of resuming the ill-fated 
"Parliamentary Hour" was included on the agenda. Apart from 
this, the faction comprising the Communists, Agrarians, 
Zhirinovskiy-ites, and "Russian Way" deputies' group and the 
"Women of Russia" affiliated to it issued a statement which 
says: "ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA and YURIDICHESKAYA GAZETA ROSSII 
should once again become parliamentary publications of the State 
Duma." 
  "Trying to revive such a program is not the way to go. It 
was devised in order to wage the war between the two branches of 
power more successfully," Mikhail Poltoranin, chairman of the 
mass media committee, told your KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA 
correspondent. 
  [Stremidlovskiy] "Mikhail Nikiforovich, if the State Duma 
does nevertheless adopt a resolution to revive `Parliamentary 
Hour,' how will you implement it?" 
  [Poltoranin] "But it is impossible to implement. 
`Parliamentary Hour' cannot return in its previous form." 
  Mikhail Poltoranin said that his committee was elaborating a 
draft law on the provision of information on state organs. The 
basic thesis is that the state organs should collaborate with 
the mass media on a voluntary basis. It is easier with state 
television: It will be instructed to allocate some airtime for 
relaying parliamentary, government, or presidential news. 

</TEXT>

