<H3> <TI>   Duma Extends Agenda, Addresses Yugoslavia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101133394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1130 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2101133394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The State Duma extended today's agenda at its 
morning session. Lawmakers decided to examine at 14:00 the 
draft of a statement on the situation in the former Yugoslavia. 
  As Speaker Ivan Rybkin announced, a report would be made by 
Sergey Lavrov, a deputy foreign minister since the First Deputy 
Foreign Minister Vitaliy Churkin had not returned from 
Yugoslavia yet. 
  Lawmaker Vyacheslav Marychev (St. Petersburg, the Liberal 
Democratic Party) requested debates on the resumption of the TV 
feature entitled "Parliamentary Hour." His request was met. 
  Marychev criticized media, above all TV, for their coverage 
of Duma discussions. 
  At LDP leader Vladimir Zhirinovskiy's demand, the Duma will 
return to the issue on the make-up of the parliamentary 
committee on geo-politics. 
  It is the only committee whose composition has not been 
endorsed by the Duma so far. Most legislators are displeased 
with the fact that of the 13 committee members, 9 are LDP 
officials. 
  Lawmakers disapproved a motion to elect a fifth vice-speaker 
from among the members, elected in one-mandate constituencies. 

</TEXT>

