<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yavlinskiy Suggests Emergency Measures for Inflation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101164294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1545 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2101164294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Oleg Velichko and Anna </F>
Melnikova] 
  [Text] Moscow January 21 TASS -- Leader of the Yavlinskiy- 
Boldyrev-Lukin faction and economist Grigory Yavlinskiy 
suggested a program of emergency measures against the inflation 
and production recession at a news conference at the State Duma 
today. 
  He informed correspondents of a forecast, according to which 
the inflation may run out of control by fall 1994 to reach 50 
per cent and the production recession may be equal to 52 per 
cent of the 1989 level. 1989 was the last year of production 
increase. 
  Speaking of priority measures against the inflation, namely 
a 
possibility to control the inflation at a level of 20 per cent 
in 1994, Grigory Yavlinskiy stressed the need to bring the 
dollar exchange rate in correspondence with the inflation 
dynamics. He said the government should be responsible for the 
exchange rate dynamics, which means the soonest conclusion of 
futures deals on sales of hard currency at a certain exchange 
rate. 
  The economist warned the government against the policy of 
easy- term credits and direct subsidies. He said they should 
immediately lower the interest rate under administrative 
regulation of the credit amount. 
  Another priority is crucial changes of a policy on benefits 
for exporters. He said Russia cannot allow hard currency to 
flow abroad. He said 15 billion dollars flew abroad in 1993 
alone. 
  He offered the government to cancel the tax on exchange rate 
difference and said everyone having hard currency accounts 
should not pay for the inflation, for which they carry no direct 
responsibility. Yavlinskiy said the cancellation of this tax 
may help to prevent money outflow. 
  The economist suggested to free statistics bodies from 
government control. 
  Yavlinskiy told ITAR-TASS his faction is ready to form a 
government capable of fulfilling this program within eight to 
nine months. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

